To secure your backend server and prevent sensitive information from being committed to Git, you should create a `.gitignore` file. This file tells Git to ignore certain files and directories.

### Common .gitignore for Backend Servers

Here is a standard `.gitignore` file for a backend server that handles common files and directories containing sensitive data or temporary build artifacts.

```
# Dependency directories
/node_modules
/vendor
/build
/dist

# Environment variables and sensitive data
.env
.env.production
.env.local
config.js
credentials.json
/secrets/
/uploads/
*.pem
*.key

# Log files and temporary files
*.log
npm-debug.log*
.DS_Store
*.swp
.idea/
.vscode/

# Database files
*.sqlite3
/db.sqlite
/db/